64":"1164","1010":"1010","1040":"1040","1104":"1104","0970":"0970","1113":"1113","1134":"1134","1056":"1056","0980":"0980","1100":"1100","about 1010":"circa 1010","about 1100":"circa 1100","about 1001":"circa 1001","Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Schotland","Scotland":"Schotland","Argylshire, , , Scotland":"Argyll, Schotland","Glenorchy, Scotland":"Glenorchy, Argyll, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Dunblane, Perthshire, Scotland":"Dunblane, Perthshire, Schotland"},"en":{"about 1010–before 1113":"about 1010–before 1113","1010–1113":"1010–1113","–1104":"–1104","–Female":"Deceased","1040–1134":"1040–1134","1056–Male":"1056–Deceased","1100–1164":"1100–1164","0980–1040":"0980–1040","0970–Female":"0970–Deceased","before 1113":"before 1113","1164":"1164","1010":"1010","1040":"1040","1104":"1104","0970":"0970","1113":"1113","1134":"1134","1056":"1056","0980":"0980","1100":"1100","about 1010":"about 1010","about 1100":"about 1100","about 1001":"about 1001","Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Argylshire, , , Scotland":"Argyll, Scotland","Glenorchy, Scotland":"Glenorchy, Argyll, Scotland, United Kingdom","Dunblane, Perthshire, Scotland":"Dunblane, Perthshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"MacGregor","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish:  see  McGregor  ."],"variants":[{"name":"McGregor","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Griogair</b> or <b>Mac Greagair</b> ‘son of <i>Griogar</i>’, Gaelic form of the personal name   Gregory  . Compare   Grierson  .","History: The Scottish Highland clan McGregor claims descent from the king of Picts and Scots Kenneth MacAlpin (Cináed mac Ailpín; 810–858  AD ). The origins of the clan are unclear. In the 13th century it was established on lands on the shores of Loch Awe and already in conflict with its neighbors of Clan Campbell. By the 16th century the McGregors had retreated deep into Glen Strae and acquired the nickname ‘Children of the Mist’. In 1603 the clan was abolished by royal edict and many members of the clan changed their surname. A year later, the chief of Clan McGregor and eleven of his followers were hanged in Edinburgh. Despite the proscription, the clan survived and supported the king in the Scottish Civil War (1644–51). The exploits of the Jacobite leader Rob Roy McGregor (1671–1734) were romanticized in a novel by Sir Walter Scott. The proscription was eventually repealed in 1774."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"\"Eoin","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Gaelic equivalent of <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."]}]},{"name":"Mór\"","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional name from <i>mór</i> ‘large, great’. This was the commonest of all girls’ names in late medieval Ireland, and has continued in use in both Ireland and Scotland to the present day."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir John \"Eoin Mór\" MacGregor was born about 1010, his father, Gregor MacGregor, was 32 and his mother, Mary, was 41. He had at least 2 sons with An English Lady of Great Beauty. He died before 1113, in Scotland."},"et":{"about 1010–before 1113":"umbes 1010–enne 1113","1010